<LP>
   A federal judge in Anchorage expanded the liability of
ship owners and operators in Alaskan pipeline oil spills. The
ruling is the first to interpret whether the Trans-Alaska
Pipeline Act of 1973 superseded a 19th century law that
limited a shipper's exposure to the cost of a vessel and its
cargo.
   U.S. District Court Judge H. Russel Holland dismissed a
claim brought by Trinidad Corp., a St. Louis shipper that
hired the S.S. Glacier Bay, which struck a rock and spilled
almost 150,000 gallons of oil into the Cook Inlet Bay in
Alaska on July 2, 1987. Commercial fishermen and fish
processors filed suit in federal court asking for more than
$104.8 million from Trinidad Corp. and British Petroleum PLC,
which had hired Trinidad to ship its oil.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Trans-Alaska Pipeline Act provides that the owner or
operator of a vessel involved in an oil spill must pay
plaintiffs the first $14 million in damages. After that, the
Trans-Alaskan Pipeline Liability Fund, which is funded by oil
companies, is obligated to pay the next $86 million in
damages. Both the shipper and the fund are liable for the
damages.
   But it was unclear whether a negligent shipper would be
liable to plaintiffs for additional damages or whether the
fund could recoup the $86 million from a negligent shipper.
   Trinidad filed a complaint with the court arguing that the
19th century law limited its liability under a negligence
claim to no more than $6.55 million, the cost of the vessel
and the cargo.
   In a rare partnership, the plaintiffs and the oil
companies filed to have Trinidad's complaint dismissed.
   "Judge Holland's order is the pivotal ruling in the
Glacier Bay litigation," says plaintiffs' attorney Gerard M.
Nolting of Faegre &amp; Benson in Minneapolis. "The shipping
industry will have great difficulty in the future in limiting
its liability in oil spill litigation in cases arising out of
Trans-Alaskan oil spills and others governed by statutes
similar to the Trans-Alaskan Pipeline Act."
   Trinidad declined to comment.
