   SURVEY SAYS 1989 legal fees rose sharply in directors' and
officers' liability cases.
   Wyatt Co., a consulting firm, studied 1,333 corporations
and found that the cost of defending D&amp;O suits last year
averaged $541,000, up 61% from $336,000 in 1988 and more than
three times the 1980 figure of $162,000.
   "That's the largest percentage increase we've ever shown,"
said Kenneth S. Wollner, a consultant in Wyatt's Chicago
office.
   Not surprisingly, litigation was the highest expense, with
1989 legal expenses averaging more than $818,000 per claim,
compared with an average of $514,000 spent on claims that
were settled. Even claims that were dropped cost an average
of $203,000, the annual survey reported.
   More increases are coming, the study said. It projects
that defense costs for D&amp;O claims brought in 1989 will
average $1.3 million by the time they are completed. "There's
a tremendous escalation in the cost of defending D&amp;O claims,"
said Mr. Wollner.
   He attributed the climb to increasingly complex D&amp;O suits
brought by shareholders, noting in particular a surge in the
cases that arise out of corporate mergers or reorganizations.
About 50% of the claims reported in the Wyatt survey involved
a shareholder action. Employee suits accounted for about 20%
and customer claims about 17%. Directors and officers of
companies involved in mergers, acquisitions or divestitures
are twice as likely to get sued as other executives, Wyatt
reported.
   Among the survey's other findings: recently adopted state
statutes designed to narrow the potential liability of
executives are having mixed results. They apparently are
discouraging some types of D&amp;O claims, particularly against
private companies.
   But the statutes are having little impact on suits brought
by shareholders and government agencies against executives of
public concerns.
